<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-554-873  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 554 873.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Feb 19 1990 v7 n8 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Singing the incompatibility blues. (developing a communicationssystem) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McQuillan, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Design, configuration and installation of a local area network(LAN) with the latest in hardware and software, graphical userinterfaces and operating systems is beyond the scope of mostusers.andP;  Frustrating incompatibilities among equipment andapplications await the uninformed user.andP;  The DOS 3.3 operatingsystem is the best bet for running the most applications, butchoosing a LAN operating system presents a whole new set ofcompatibility problems.andP;  Some people await OS/2 LAN Manager andthe next generation of hardware and software, believing that allincompatibility problems will go away.andP;  Another answer is to usevalue-added resellers to configure LANs.andP;  Value-added resellers,by working daily with LAN installation and keeping abreast ofknown incompatibilities, are best able to design a successful LAN.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CompatibilityCompatible SoftwareLocal Area NetworksValue-Added ResellersOperating SystemsDecision Making.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>